<p>Yeah, a post about how to build a blog. Because owning a blog
      means that at least 20% of your posts need to be about the tech used in it's own creation. But
      this one is different. It's the tech used to upgrade a legacy Blogger site to a more modern
      responsive layout <span class="emoji">ðŸ˜ƒ</span></p><h2 style="text-align:
      left;"><span class="emoji">Why?</span></h2><p style="text-align:
      left;"><span class="emoji">Well, while simultaneously an item of pride and
      embarrassment, I've had this Uncommented Bytes blog running for 17+ years somehow. (And more
      like 18-19 years but I lost the first bit of it when jRoller, the best hosted blog engine,
      went under and required the original migration to
      Blogger.)&nbsp;</span></p><p style="text-align: left;"><span
      class="emoji">I wrote <a
      href="https://www.sheetsj.com/2021/01/loading-local-test-data-in-spring-boot.html">a post
      for the first time in a while</a>, and was pretty annoyed with how it looked on
      mobile</span></p><table align="center" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0"
      class="tr-caption-container" style="margin-left: auto; margin-right:
      auto;"><tbody><tr><td style="text-align: center;"><img alt=""
      border="0" width="320" data-original-height="406" data-original-width="1170"
      src="https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/img/b/R29vZ2xl/AVvXsEiidXON6yZhUvffWFQceFaz2UduRRJQi-bybuBMhC8EDNB7updj6NCH62XLzNuheO-yu5LpzTfLMVyutT4nPiJlhIN0QA4zdBVa_CMsSt9tP0g_eYMqTLe5czEFtXbKMs1DMMhgGr6prt6SfanGH7oDNqTlE1hcjwmhDaCJZiEU1OGaBAFj6A/s320/tweet.png"/></td></tr><tr><td
      class="tr-caption" style="text-align: center;"><a
      href="https://twitter.com/sheetsj/status/1352434228483514371">https://twitter.com/sheetsj/status/1352434228483514371</a></td></tr></tbody></table><p
      style="text-align: left;"><span class="emoji"></span></p><p
      style="text-align: left;"><span class="emoji">I originally had a green-ish theme, and
      thought I'd tweak it to be responsive. But even though it was simple-ish, it was using some
      images for backgrounds and shading that were just overwhelming to try to update in the
      super-wordy blogger html template. (look at that beautifully retro Google+ link)<br
      /></span></p><table align="center" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0"
      class="tr-caption-container" style="margin-left: auto; margin-right:
      auto;"><tbody><tr><td style="text-align: center;"><img alt=""
      height="349"
      src="data:image/png;base64,"
      style="margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;" width="517"
      /></td></tr><tr><td class="tr-caption" style="text-align:
      center;"><a
      href="https://web.archive.org/web/20181227163052/http://uncommentedbytes.blogspot.com/">https://web.archive.org/web/20181227163052/http://uncommentedbytes.blogspot.com/</a></td></tr></tbody></table><p
      style="text-align: left;"><span class="emoji">So I decided to "upgrade" to a cleaner
      look theme in <a
      href="http://blogs.harvard.edu/lamont/2012/11/29/blogger-default-templates-which-one-is-the-best/">Awesome,
      Inc</a> --- which despite the genius name, was lacking in a couple
      areas:</span></p><ol style="text-align: left;"><li><span
      class="emoji">Fixed margins -- meaning not responsive to browser
      width</span></li><li><span class="emoji">No mobile friendly view --
      mostly because it wasn't responsive, but also because I had used a Blogger switch to render a
      super generic mobile view too (which I think was triggered by user agent headers, yikes)
      <br /></span></li></ol><h2 style="text-align: left;"><span
      class="emoji">How?</span></h2><p style="text-align: left;"><span
      class="emoji">Trial-and-error isn't fun to describe, especially when it mostly involves
      browser devtools CSS hacking. But basically I took the super-wordy HTML template and hacked in
      some CSS Grid layout. 90% of the hack-magic was accomplished with this
      bit:</span></p><pre> div.content {
      display: grid;
      gap: 20px;
      grid-template-areas:
      "header"
      "content"
      "sidebar"
      "footer";
      max-width: 100vw;
      margin: 0 auto;
      }
      </pre><p>Plus a tiny bit of responsive handling:</p><pre> @media
      (min-width: 800px) {
      div.content {
      grid-template-columns: 2fr 1fr;
      grid-template-areas:
      "header header"
      "content sidebar"
      "footer footer";
      max-width: 1280px;
      }
      }
      @media (min-width: 1024px) {
      div.content {
      grid-template-columns: 4fr 1fr;
      }
      }
      .gist .blob-code-inner {
      white-space: pre-wrap !important;
      }</pre><p>And the last 10% was a few margin and padding tweaks sprinkled in other
      places. You can see the full code in my <a
      href="https://github.com/jeffsheets/blogger-css-grid-layout">Github blogger-css-grid-layout
      project</a>. And just in case I redesign again in the future, the full inception final
      product looks like this today:</p><p><img alt="" height="349"
      src="data:image/png;base64,"
      width="655" />&nbsp;</p><h2 style="text-align: left;">Why Blogger in
      2021?</h2><p style="text-align: left;">I'm glad you asked. I thought about <a
      href="https://www.11ty.dev/">converting all of this to 11ty</a>, which really is
      still on the ole TODO list. But there's a few hurdles in conversion -- mainly images, code
      formatting, preserving URLs to not break old incoming links, and preserving comments (as minor
      as they are). And I started to get paralyzed by these thoughts, and really I just wanted
      something that looked a little more modern than I previously had.</p><p
      style="text-align: left;">Also Blogger does a couple of things pretty well. Namely:<br
      /></p><ul style="text-align: left;"><li>It has a simple Compose/HTML
      editor</li><li>It handles images very easily, by simply pasting in
      screenshots</li><li>I don't have to think about
      it.</li></ul><p>Does it have it's issues? Yeah. It is tied to Google, so
      even though it has been around many years, I'm sure they'll kill it at some point. It's
      server-side rendered, so the performance would definitely be better in 11ty or another
      JAMStack tech. So I'll keep migration on the TODO list for future me to deal with!<br
      /></p>
